/* Mark V: 1984–1990 */ Changed "original Mini Cooper" to "original Mini Cooper S" -- the "Cooper S" was always considered almost as a different marque; it was never referred to as a type of "Cooper".  As with all contemporary Mini engines, they both had "A"-series engines. The Mini Coopers originally had a strange long-stroke 997 cc engine and later a squarer 998 cc engine.  The Ss had first a 1070 cc, then a "homologation special" oversquare 970 cc engine for racing, then a 1275 cc.

Automated manual transmission, not semi-automatic. Semi-automatic transmissions haven't been used in automobiles since the 1980s, or the early-1990s. Also, corrected numerous spelling and grammatical errors.

/* EuroNCAP performance */ Wikipedia is not the place to run "defence" for the subject of the article. EuroNCAP tests simulate real life situations, so arguing that the car wasn't specifically designed for the tests is, not only nonsense but also, irrelevant to the fact it scored poorly.

Electric Motors are not Engines, this is grammatically incorrect. An engine converts energy within itself (i.e from a fuel) and then applies that power mechanically, whereas a motor would convert energy created elsewhere to motive force.  Additionally, the same information (that it is 30kW) is covered in the EV section immediately following it, "===Elettra===". If this group wants to keep this as a hook sentence for the Elettra section, i would recommend describing it as an electric motor.
